
7.1.1 - W11SR01: Excessive Local Administrative Privileges on Stand-alone Workstations
ISM controls:

Control: 1175; Revision: 4; Updated: Jun-21; Applicability: All; OS: All (Restricting administrative privileges)

Control: 1507; Revision: 3; Updated: Dec-23; Applicability: All; OS: All (Privileged access to systems and applications)

Control: 0957; Revision: 7; Updated: Sep-23; Applicability: All; OS: All (Restricting access to systems and applications)

Current Risk
Insufficient implementation of user identity and access management processes and / or controls leads to a compromise of the system and its data. The excessive use of local Administrator rights for Stand-alone Workstations may lead to the compromise of the agency system and / or its data, including the ability to disable security functions and tools.

Risk Assessment:

Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
ALMOST CERTAIN	x	MAJOR	=	EXTREME
Recommendations:

Enforce Principle of Least Privilege: Remove local administrative rights from all standard user accounts on stand-alone workstations, ensuring users operate with standard user permissions for daily tasks.

Implement Local Administrator Password Solution (LAPS): Use a managed solution to rotate and secure unique local administrator passwords for each workstation, preventing lateral movement.

Formalise Privileged Access Management: Establish a strict approval process and audit trail for any temporary elevation of privileges required for technical maintenance.

- Treatment #1

Privileged User Audit: Conduct a comprehensive review of all current local accounts on stand-alone machines and immediately revoke unnecessary administrative memberships.

Technical Policy Enforcement: Deploy local group policy objects (GPOs) or configuration profiles that explicitly define and restrict the members of the local "Administrators" group.

Standard Operating Environment (SOE) Hardening: Update the stand-alone workstation SOE image to ensure that new deployments default to standard user profiles with no inherent administrative access.

Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
Removing standing administrative access significantly reduces the primary vector for system-wide compromise and the disabling of security tools. While the consequence of a potential compromise remains "Major" due to the sensitivity of the standalone environment, the likelihood is reduced from "Almost Certain" to "Rare," as an attacker would require an additional, high-complexity exploit to gain elevated persistence.

Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
RARE	x	MAJOR	=	MEDIUM
